# Mobile Operator Console Design System

The mobile/tablet operator panel is **not** a responsive copy of desktop. It is a
dedicated Auction Operating Console for one-handed use under pressure. Apply
this to every current and future mobile operator screen (Auction, Queue,
Teams, Broadcast, and any new operator surface).

## 1. Action first
Anything that performs an action (Start Bidding, Next Player, Sold, Unsold,
Defer, Manual Sell, Pause) outranks anything read-only (purse, stats, history,
team/player details, queue counts). Buttons are always visually larger than
info cards — never give them equal weight.

## 2. Button hierarchy (mobile)
Biggest, thumb-reachable, no-scroll-required: **Start Bidding, Next Player,
Sold, Unsold**. Slightly smaller: **Defer, Manual Sell**. Everything else
(reauction, timers, quick bid roster) is visually smaller still.

## 3. Info density
Read-only content (team cards, purse, queue counters, bid history, player
stats) must be compact — minimal vertical space, small type. Never let a
read-only card compete for space with an action button.

## 4. Player photo
Desktop/LED: large photo. **Mobile: thumbnail only (~25% photo / 75% info)**
— the operator already knows the player; the photo is just confirmation.

## 5. Color system — max 5 semantic colors
- **Green** = success (Sold, Active, Start)
- **Red** = danger (Unsold, Delete, Stop)
- **Yellow/Amber** = warning (Pause, Next Player, Defer)
- **Blue** = info (Manual, Queue)
- **Neutral gray** = everything else
Don't invent a new accent color per feature.

## 6. One responsibility per screen
- **Auction** — live auction ops only (player, bid, sold/unsold/defer/manual, timers). No unrelated read-only panels.
- **Queue** — search/filter/push-to-auction only. Automatic order ⇒ disable editing + show info message. Manual order ⇒ full management.
- **Teams** (was "Reference") — read-only: purse, squad, max bid, remaining slots, reserve purse, recent purchases. No auction controls.
- **Broadcast** — LED (Main/Team/Player/Top5/Banner) + OBS (Live/Team/Player/Top5) + Utilities (Break Timer, Fortune Wheel, Booster) only.
Never duplicate the same control across screens.

## 7. Header
Compact 2-row mobile/tablet header: (1) logo + tournament name + live + back,
(2) SOLD • LEFT • ACTIVE + session control (Pause/Start/Conclude). Never put
LED/OBS/MAIN/QUICK controls on the Auction screen — those belong only in
Broadcast. Desktop header stays unchanged.

## 8. Touch & layout
- Min touch target 44px, prefer 56–72px for the primary 4 (Start/Next/Sold/Unsold).
- No horizontal scrolling, ever.
- Primary controls must render above the fold without scrolling; secondary content (timers, quick bid, history) can require a scroll.
- Test at 320/360/390/412/768/1024px. Browser and APK (Capacitor/PWA) must render identically — no platform-specific layout branches.

## 9. Performance
Avoid heavy animation/transition on the hot path (Sold/Unsold/Next Player).
Prefer instant visual feedback over decorative motion.

## 10. Desktop is out of scope
Never change desktop behavior/layout to satisfy a mobile requirement. Always
implement mobile-only views via `lg:hidden` / `hidden lg:flex` siblings (or
shared extracted JSX constants rendered in each), not by altering the shared
desktop tree.
